defaultThird party interventions default&#xa0;defaultCosts – legal aiddefault&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default‘If a person with a potential claim cannot get legal aid, there are two possible consequences. The first is 
defaultthat the claim is dropped: that is a rank denial of justice and a blot on the rule of law. The second is that the claim is pursued, in which case it will be pursued inefficiently, and will take up much more of the court staffs’ time and of the judge’s time
default in and out of court. So that it means greater costs for the court system and in delay for other litigants’.
